1. Introduction-
The Virtual Piano is a real-time computer vision application that allows users to play musical notes by moving their hands in front of a webcam. This project
eliminates the need for physical hardware or touch interfaces, using motion tracking and color segmentation to trigger audio frequencies.

2. Objectives-
> To develop a touchless interface for musical expression.
> To implement real-time skin color detection using the HSV color space.
> To map spatial coordinates of detected objects to specific musical frequencies ($261.63$ Hz to $523.25$ Hz).

3. Methodology & Technical Implementation-
The system follows a linear pipeline of image processing and decision-making:

  A. Video Capture and Preprocessing- 
    > Frame Acquisition: The system captures video at the hardware's default resolution using cv2.VideoCapture.
    > Mirroring: The frame is flipped horizontally using cv2.flip(frame, 1) to provide a natural "mirror" interaction for the user.
    > Color Conversion: Frames are converted from BGR to HSV to improve the robustness of skin detection under varying lighting.
  B. Hand Detection (Skin Masking): The core interaction relies on a skin-tone mask defined by specific HSV boundaries:
    > Lower Boundary: [0, 40, 60]
    > Upper Boundary: [20, 255, 255]
  Any pixels falling within this range are converted to a white mask, while all others become black.
  C. Spatial Mapping (The "Hot Zone"):-
    > Region of Interest (ROI): The system only monitors the top $60$ pixels of the frame.
    > Contour Analysis: The largest white object in the ROI is identified as the hand.
    > Centroid Calculation: The $x$-coordinate of the hand is calculated using Image Moments ($M_{10}/M_{00}$).
  D. Audio Synthesis: The screen is divided into $8$ equal sections.The calculated $x$-coordinate determines which "key" is active.The winsound.Beep function generates the tone 
  based on the FREQUENCIES array.

4. Hardware and Software Requirements-
Component                 Specification
Operating System          Windows (for winsound support)
Language                  Python 3.x
Libraries                 OpenCV (cv2), NumPy, winsound
Hardware                  Standard USB or Integrated Webcam

5. Results and Observations-
  > Responsiveness: The system triggers notes immediately upon the hand entering a new segment.
  > Visual Feedback: The interface draws green rectangles over the active "key" to confirm user input.
  > Limitations: Performance is highly dependent on lighting; dark environments may result in "noisy" detection or failure to trigger notes.

6. Conclusion-
The project successfully demonstrates a functional gestural interface. By combining spatial partitioning with color-based object tracking, it creates an 
intuitive and accessible virtual instrument.
